<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,953,384,408]" box="[160,953,384,408]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<typeStatus box="[160,214,384,408]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Cavalleri, Souza, Prezotto and Mound." box="[319,953,384,408]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mirothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[319,512,384,408]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Mirothrips bicolor</emphasis>
Cavalleri, Souza, Prezotto and Mound.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1156,450,994]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
This recently described genus now comprises four Neotropical species that are closely related to 
<emphasis box="[277,420,485,509]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watson" authorityYear="1923" box="[277,417,485,509]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Karnyothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Karnyothrips</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[427,625,485,509]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mirothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[427,537,485,509]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Mirothrips</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
are easily recognisable by the presence of two pairs of setae on the metanotum arising medially, and by the long and slender antennal segment 
<collectionCode box="[266,300,554,578]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">VIII</collectionCode>
which is constricted at the base (
<bibRefCitation author="Cavalleri A &amp; De Souza AR &amp; Prezoto F &amp; Mound LA" box="[682,905,554,578]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" pagination="332 - 341" refId="ref9081" refString="Cavalleri A, De Souza AR, Prezoto F, Mound LA. 2013. Egg predation within the nests of social wasps: a new genus and species of Phlaeothripidae and evolutionary consequences of Thysanoptera invasive behaviour. Biol J Linn Soc. 109: 332 - 341." type="journal article" year="2013">Cavalleri et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). The maxillary stylets are remarkably low and widely separated, and males bear sternal pore plates on segment 
<collectionCode box="[269,306,623,647]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">VIII</collectionCode>
. The antennal sense cone formula is variable amongst species, with two or three on III and usually three or four on IV, although the number of sense cones on IV varies from two to four in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Santis" baseAuthorityYear="1959" box="[470,570,693,717]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mirothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">
<emphasis box="[470,570,693,717]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">M. analis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We studied the 
<typeStatus box="[771,821,693,717]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">type</typeStatus>
series of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cavalleri &amp; Lindner &amp; Mendonça Jr" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Cavalleri &amp; Lindner &amp; Mendonça Jr" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[936,1155,693,717]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mirothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespicola" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[936,1155,693,717]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Mirothrips vespicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[160,293,727,751]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<bibRefCitation author="De Santis L" box="[313,497,727,751]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" pagination="1 - 3" refId="ref9280" refString="De Santis L. 1980. Description of a new species of Thysanoptera (Insecta) from Brazil with notes about others from Argentina. Dusenia. 12: 1 - 3. Spanish." type="journal article" year="1980">De Santis 1980</bibRefCitation>
) at 
<collectionCode box="[556,607,727,751]" country="Argentina" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/66si-588n" name="Museo de La Plata" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">MLP</collectionCode>
, collected from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="de Saussure" baseAuthorityYear="1954" box="[809,1082,727,751]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Mischocyttarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="drewseni">
<emphasis box="[809,1082,727,751]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Mischocyttarus drewseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nests (
<taxonomicName box="[166,324,762,786]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[337,440,762,786]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Vespidae</taxonomicName>
) in Curitiba, South 
<collectingCountry box="[669,732,762,786]" name="Brazil" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. This species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cavalleri, Souza, Prezotto &amp; Mound" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mirothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arbiter">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">M. arbiter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in which adults and larvae feed on the eggs of polistine wasps in Southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[160,220,831,855]" name="Brazil" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cavalleri A &amp; De Souza AR &amp; Prezoto F &amp; Mound LA" box="[234,457,831,855]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" pagination="332 - 341" refId="ref9081" refString="Cavalleri A, De Souza AR, Prezoto F, Mound LA. 2013. Egg predation within the nests of social wasps: a new genus and species of Phlaeothripidae and evolutionary consequences of Thysanoptera invasive behaviour. Biol J Linn Soc. 109: 332 - 341." type="journal article" year="2013">Cavalleri et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). They both have the major body setae unusually translucent and stout, although these structures are thicker at the tip in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cavalleri, Souza, Prezotto &amp; Mound" authorityYear="2013" box="[860,967,866,890]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mirothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arbiter">
<emphasis box="[860,967,866,890]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">M. arbiter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These two taxa are likely to exhibit similar biology, and they can be separated using the key below. All 
<taxonomicName box="[160,362,935,959]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mirothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[160,270,935,959]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Mirothrips</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
are presumably predatory on small arthropods and are known only from South America.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" type="key">
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,906,1039,1064]" box="[160,906,1039,1064]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,906,1039,1064]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
Key to 
<taxonomicName box="[247,464,1039,1064]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mirothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[247,368,1039,1064]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Mirothrips</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
(adapted from 
<bibRefCitation author="Cavalleri A &amp; De Souza AR &amp; Prezoto F &amp; Mound LA" box="[656,898,1039,1063]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" pagination="332 - 341" refId="ref9081" refString="Cavalleri A, De Souza AR, Prezoto F, Mound LA. 2013. Egg predation within the nests of social wasps: a new genus and species of Phlaeothripidae and evolutionary consequences of Thysanoptera invasive behaviour. Biol J Linn Soc. 109: 332 - 341." type="journal article" year="2013">Cavalleri et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<key pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<keyStep pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1156,1091,1219]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<keyLead pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
1. Body bicoloured, abdominal segments I–VIII yellow, IX–X dark brown; legs yellow, also antennal segments III–V............................................... ............................................... 
<taxonomicName box="[1075,1155,1125,1150]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mirothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1075,1155,1125,1150]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1156,1091,1219]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<keyLead pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">− Body brown including abdomen, also mid and hind femora, tibiae and antennal segments III–V........................................................................................................................................ 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1156,1253,1519]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<keyLead pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
2. Antennal segments VI and VII not elongate, VI about 1.8 as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[1037,1142,1253,1277]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="12.[160,225,976,999]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,945]" captionTargetId="figure-162@12.[163,1153,142,946]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 4. Mirothrips species. (A–E) Mirothrips arbiter. (F) Mirothrips analis. (G–I) Mirothrips vespicola. (A) Metanotum, with two pairs of setae (arrows). (B) Prosternum, with two pairs of long setae (arrows). (C) Pronotum. (D) Tube, with setae S1 shorter than tube (arrow). (E–G) Antenna. (H) Head and pronotum. (I) Tube, with setae S1 about as long as tube (arrow)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5206286" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5206286/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Figure 4F</figureCitation>
); antennal segment III with two sense cones; major setae on head, pronotum and tergites slender and tapering to just below capitate apex, more slender than stoutest pair of tergal sigmoid setae........................................ ........................................ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Santis" baseAuthorityYear="1959" box="[1085,1155,1356,1381]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mirothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1085,1155,1356,1381]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">analis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1156,1253,1519]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<keyLead pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
− Antennal segments VI and VII elongate, VI about 2.3 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[217,357,1426,1450]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="12.[160,225,976,999]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,945]" captionTargetId="figure-162@12.[163,1153,142,946]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 4. Mirothrips species. (A–E) Mirothrips arbiter. (F) Mirothrips analis. (G–I) Mirothrips vespicola. (A) Metanotum, with two pairs of setae (arrows). (B) Prosternum, with two pairs of long setae (arrows). (C) Pronotum. (D) Tube, with setae S1 shorter than tube (arrow). (E–G) Antenna. (H) Head and pronotum. (I) Tube, with setae S1 about as long as tube (arrow)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5206286" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5206286/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Figure 4E, G</figureCitation>
); antennal segment III with three sense cones; major setae on head, pronotum and tergites unusually stout and parallel sided, considerably thicker medially than the stoutest pair of tergal sigmoid setae (
<figureCitation box="[849,989,1495,1519]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="12.[160,225,976,999]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,945]" captionTargetId="figure-162@12.[163,1153,142,946]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 4. Mirothrips species. (A–E) Mirothrips arbiter. (F) Mirothrips analis. (G–I) Mirothrips vespicola. (A) Metanotum, with two pairs of setae (arrows). (B) Prosternum, with two pairs of long setae (arrows). (C) Pronotum. (D) Tube, with setae S1 shorter than tube (arrow). (E–G) Antenna. (H) Head and pronotum. (I) Tube, with setae S1 about as long as tube (arrow)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5206286" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5206286/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Figure 4C, H</figureCitation>
)........... ........... 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1156,1547,1675]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<keyLead pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
3. Pelta with paired campaniform sensilla; S1 on tergite IX less than 0.7 times as long as tube (
<figureCitation box="[311,422,1582,1606]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="12.[160,225,976,999]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,945]" captionTargetId="figure-162@12.[163,1153,142,946]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 4. Mirothrips species. (A–E) Mirothrips arbiter. (F) Mirothrips analis. (G–I) Mirothrips vespicola. (A) Metanotum, with two pairs of setae (arrows). (B) Prosternum, with two pairs of long setae (arrows). (C) Pronotum. (D) Tube, with setae S1 shorter than tube (arrow). (E–G) Antenna. (H) Head and pronotum. (I) Tube, with setae S1 about as long as tube (arrow)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5206286" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5206286/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Figure 4D</figureCitation>
)......................................................... ......................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cavalleri, Souza, Prezotto &amp; Mound" authorityYear="2013" box="[1076,1155,1581,1606]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mirothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arbiter">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1076,1155,1581,1606]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">arbiter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1156,1547,1675]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
<keyLead pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">
− Pelta without campaniform sensilla; S1 on tergite IX sub equal in length to the tube (
<figureCitation box="[217,317,1651,1675]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="12.[160,225,976,999]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,945]" captionTargetId="figure-162@12.[163,1153,142,946]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 4. Mirothrips species. (A–E) Mirothrips arbiter. (F) Mirothrips analis. (G–I) Mirothrips vespicola. (A) Metanotum, with two pairs of setae (arrows). (B) Prosternum, with two pairs of long setae (arrows). (C) Pronotum. (D) Tube, with setae S1 shorter than tube (arrow). (E–G) Antenna. (H) Head and pronotum. (I) Tube, with setae S1 about as long as tube (arrow)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5206286" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5206286/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="1406">Figure 4I</figureCitation>
)........................................................................................................ 
